<paragraph id="217E36CCAC63FFBD55E0FA41FEC9FA44" blockId="13.[189,335,1506,1532]" box="[189,335,1506,1532]" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">
<heading id="7A3681A0AC63FFBD55E0FA41FEC9FA44" bold="true" box="[189,335,1506,1532]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="13" pageNumber="153" reason="3">
<emphasis id="13B5EADEAC63FFBD55E0FA41FEC9FA44" bold="true" box="[189,335,1506,1532]" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC63FFBD55E0F9B3FE6CF9C9" blockId="13.[189,1399,1552,1649]" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">
Elevated shell with rounded whorls and flattened apex, irregular axial sculpture of raised ribs and spiral cordlets, flexuous lip and smooth protoconch, cream white. 
<typeStatus id="FE7A886EAC63FFBD5628F997FC64F9F6" box="[885,994,1588,1614]" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">Holotype</typeStatus>
dimensions: height 
<quantity id="E6399B29AC63FFBD5190F997FAAFF9F6" box="[1229,1321,1588,1614]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="13" pageNumber="153" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
, width 
<quantity id="E6399B29AC63FFBD55E0F9F4FE9CF9C9" box="[189,282,1623,1649]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="13" pageNumber="153" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.6 mm</quantity>
, apical angle 36°.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC63FFBD55E0F93AFEF0F96E" blockId="13.[188,1398,1687,1750]" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">
PROTOCONCH. Flattened paucispiral shell with 1¼ whorls (
<figureCitation id="B9FA2A49AC63FFBD5604F93BFB8DF90B" box="[857,1035,1688,1715]" captionStart="Figs 51–56" captionStartId="14.[189,242,1806,1832]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetId="figure-173@14.[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 51–56. Talassia rugosa sp. nov., Angola, Castle Mounds, M122-GeoB20958. 51–54. Holotype (SMF358973). 51. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.1 mm. 52–53. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm. 54. Sculpture body whorl. 55–56. Paratype (SMF358974).55. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.2 mm. 56. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm, arrow indicates lip. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6564561" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6564561/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">Figs 52–53, 56</figureCitation>
); smooth; lip straight (
<figureCitation id="B9FA2A49AC63FFBD504CF93BFAEEF90B" box="[1297,1384,1688,1715]" captionStart="Figs 51–56" captionStartId="14.[189,242,1806,1832]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetId="figure-173@14.[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 51–56. Talassia rugosa sp. nov., Angola, Castle Mounds, M122-GeoB20958. 51–54. Holotype (SMF358973). 51. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.1 mm. 52–53. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm. 54. Sculpture body whorl. 55–56. Paratype (SMF358974).55. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.2 mm. 56. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm, arrow indicates lip. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6564561" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6564561/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">Fig. 56</figureCitation>
); width 
<quantity id="E6399B29AC63FFBD545BF91FFEF4F96E" box="[262,370,1724,1750]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" pageId="13" pageNumber="153" unit="mm" value="0.34">0.34 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC63FFBD55E0F95EFC6EF839" blockId="13.[189,1399,1789,1921]" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">
TELEOCONCH. Elevated spire with 4 rounded whorls and deep suture (
<figureCitation id="B9FA2A49AC63FFBD56B5F95EFBF4F8A0" box="[1000,1138,1789,1816]" captionStart="Figs 51–56" captionStartId="14.[189,242,1806,1832]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetId="figure-173@14.[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 51–56. Talassia rugosa sp. nov., Angola, Castle Mounds, M122-GeoB20958. 51–54. Holotype (SMF358973). 51. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.1 mm. 52–53. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm. 54. Sculpture body whorl. 55–56. Paratype (SMF358974).55. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.2 mm. 56. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm, arrow indicates lip. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6564561" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6564561/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">Figs 51, 55</figureCitation>
). Axial sculpture with irregularly spaced slightly flexuous ribs and numerous growth lines. Irregularly-spaced spiral cordlets composed of sets of closely-aligned lines of various strength; lines composed of raised dots (
<figureCitation id="B9FA2A49AC63FFBD504DF8E0FAEFF8E6" box="[1296,1385,1859,1886]" captionStart="Figs 51–56" captionStartId="14.[189,242,1806,1832]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetId="figure-173@14.[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 51–56. Talassia rugosa sp. nov., Angola, Castle Mounds, M122-GeoB20958. 51–54. Holotype (SMF358973). 51. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.1 mm. 52–53. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm. 54. Sculpture body whorl. 55–56. Paratype (SMF358974).55. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.2 mm. 56. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm, arrow indicates lip. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6564561" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6564561/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">Fig. 54</figureCitation>
). Umbilicus nearly completely covered by columellar lip (
<figureCitation id="B9FA2A49AC63FFBD560AF8C5FC5DF839" box="[855,987,1894,1921]" captionStart="Figs 51–56" captionStartId="14.[189,242,1806,1832]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetId="figure-173@14.[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 51–56. Talassia rugosa sp. nov., Angola, Castle Mounds, M122-GeoB20958. 51–54. Holotype (SMF358973). 51. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.1 mm. 52–53. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm. 54. Sculpture body whorl. 55–56. Paratype (SMF358974).55. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.2 mm. 56. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm, arrow indicates lip. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6564561" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6564561/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="153">Fig. 51, 55</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC60FFBE55E0FEAAFE7DFED1" blockId="14.[189,1400,265,362]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">
APERTURE. Oval outline, slightly concave on parietal side; smooth inside (
<figureCitation id="B9FA2A49AC60FFBE5174FEAAFB32FE9C" box="[1065,1204,265,292]" captionStart="Figs 51–56" captionStartId="14.[189,242,1806,1832]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetId="figure-173@14.[189,1398,1017,1767]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Figs 51–56. Talassia rugosa sp. nov., Angola, Castle Mounds, M122-GeoB20958. 51–54. Holotype (SMF358973). 51. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.1 mm. 52–53. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm. 54. Sculpture body whorl. 55–56. Paratype (SMF358974).55. Ventral view, H = 3.2 mm, W = 1.6 mm, Ha = 1.2 mm. 56. Protoconch, Wp = 0.34 mm, arrow indicates lip. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6564561" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6564561/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">Figs 51, 55</figureCitation>
). Columellar lip sharp; external lip not thickened, blunt, flexuous with notches above periphery and at base. Aperture height 
<quantity id="E6399B29AC60FFBE5453FEECFEEEFED2" box="[270,360,335,362]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.1" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" unit="mm" value="1.1">1.1 mm</quantity>
in 
<typeStatus id="FE7A886EAC60FFBE54D0FEECFE7EFED1" box="[397,504,335,361]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC60FFBE55E0FE32FBB1FE13" blockId="14.[189,1079,401,427]" box="[189,1079,401,427]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">
VARIABILITY. Little variability observed. Observed adult height 3.0– 
<quantity id="E6399B29AC60FFBE5688FE32FBB4FE13" box="[981,1074,401,427]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.2" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" unit="mm" value="3.2">3.2 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="69DB6547AC60FFBE55E0FE71FD79FDA3" box="[189,767,466,539]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC60FFBE55E0FE71FEDEFE54" blockId="14.[189,344,466,492]" box="[189,344,466,492]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">
<heading id="7A3681A0AC60FFBE55E0FE71FEDEFE54" bold="true" box="[189,344,466,492]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" reason="3">
<emphasis id="13B5EADEAC60FFBE55E0FE71FEDEFE54" bold="true" box="[189,344,466,492]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC60FFBE55E0FDA2FD79FDA3" blockId="14.[189,767,513,539]" box="[189,767,513,539]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">
The species is only known from the 
<typeStatus id="FE7A886EAC60FFBE573AFDA2FD1CFDA3" box="[615,666,513,539]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="69DB6547AC60FFBE55E0FDE1FC15FD33" box="[189,915,578,651]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC60FFBE55E0FDE1FEB6FDE4" blockId="14.[189,304,578,604]" box="[189,304,578,604]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">
<heading id="7A3681A0AC60FFBE55E0FDE1FEB6FDE4" bold="true" box="[189,304,578,604]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" reason="3">
<emphasis id="13B5EADEAC60FFBE55E0FDE1FEB6FDE4" bold="true" box="[189,304,578,604]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC60FFBE55E0FDD2FC15FD33" blockId="14.[189,915,625,651]" box="[189,915,625,651]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">The radula and the soft parts of the new species are unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="69DB6547AC60FFBE55E0FD11FB02FC3F" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC60FFBE55E0FD11FE4AFD74" blockId="14.[189,460,690,716]" box="[189,460,690,716]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">
<heading id="7A3681A0AC60FFBE55E0FD11FE4AFD74" bold="true" box="[189,460,690,716]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" reason="3">
<emphasis id="13B5EADEAC60FFBE55E0FD11FE4AFD74" bold="true" box="[189,460,690,716]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">Differential diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="217E36CCAC60FFBE55E0FD42FB02FC3F" blockId="14.[188,1399,737,904]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">
<taxonomicName id="E6C14D4FAC60FFBE55E0FD42FE1CFD43" baseAuthorityName="de Folin" baseAuthorityYear="1873" box="[189,410,737,763]" class="Gastropoda" family="Vanikoridae" genus="Talassia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="dagueneti">
<emphasis id="13B5EADEAC60FFBE55E0FD42FE1CFD43" box="[189,410,737,763]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">Talassia dagueneti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a similar teleoconch sculpture but its axial sculpture is more regular and lacks the spiral cordlets and its protoconch has a stronger spiral sculpture and a more elevated outline (
<bibRefCitation id="45504B3DAC60FFBE5055FCA7FEE0FCF9" author="Waren A. &amp; Bouchet Ph." pageId="14" pageNumber="154" pagination="73 - 100" refId="ref9418" refString="Waren A. &amp; Bouchet Ph. 1988. A new species of Vanikoridae from the western Mediterranean, with remarks on the Northeast Atlantic species of the family. Bollettino Malacologico 24 (5 - 8): 73 - 100." type="journal article" year="1988">Warén &amp; Bouchet 1988</bibRefCitation>
; 
<figureCitation id="B9FA2A49AC60FFBE542EFC84FE5DFCF9" box="[371,475,807,833]" captionStart="Figs 1–11" captionStartId="3.[188,241,1752,1778]" captionTargetBox="[269,1319,265,1714]" captionTargetId="figure-19@3.[269,1319,265,1714]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Figs 1–11. Talassia Warén &amp; Bouchet, 1988 from the NE Atlantic. 1–3. Talassia coriacea (Manzoni, 1868), off Funchal, Madeira, depth 70 m (SaM74968). 1. Ventral view, H = 2.7, W = 1.5 mm, Ha = 1.2 mm. 2. Protoconch, Wp = 0.37 mm. 3. Sculpture body whorl. 4–7. Talassia dagueneti (de Folin, 1873), Porcupine Seabight, Galway Mound, POS316-524 (SaM). 4–5. Side view, H = 2.5 mm. 5. Protoconch, Wp = 0.32 mm. 6–7. Ventral view, H = 2.3 mm, W = 1.0 mm. 7. Sculpture body whorl. 8–11. Talassia tenuisculpta (R.B. Watson, 1873), Azores, Mar da Prata, M151-GeoB23111 (SaM). 8–10. Ventral view, H = 2.6 mm, W = 1.3 mm. 9–10. Protoconch, Wp 0.40 mm, arrow indicates lip. 11. Side view, H = 2.3 mm. Scale bars = 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6564547" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6564547/files/figure.png" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">Figs 4–7</figureCitation>
) whereas 
<taxonomicName id="E6C14D4FAC60FFBE5708FC8BFD40FCF9" authority="Hoffman &amp; Freiwald, 2022" authorityName="Hoffman &amp; Freiwald" authorityYear="2022" box="[597,710,808,833]" class="Gastropoda" family="Vanikoridae" genus="Talassia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="rugosa" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="13B5EADEAC60FFBE5708FC8BFD40FCF9" box="[597,710,808,833]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">T. rugosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="088657A5AC60FFBE5793FC8BFCAFFCFA" box="[718,809,808,834]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has a more conical outline, an irregular sculpture with spiral cordlets and a smooth protoconch with a flattened outline. 
<taxonomicName id="E6C14D4FAC60FFBE56AAFCE9FB54FCDC" authority="Hoffman &amp; Freiwald, 2022" authorityName="Hoffman &amp; Freiwald" authorityYear="2022" box="[1015,1234,842,868]" class="Gastropoda" family="Vanikoridae" genus="Talassia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="mexicana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="13B5EADEAC60FFBE56AAFCE9FB54FCDC" box="[1015,1234,842,868]" italics="true" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">Talassia mexicana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="088657A5AC60FFBE5186FCE8FAB0FCDD" box="[1243,1334,843,869]" pageId="14" pageNumber="154" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
from the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion id="E305F82EAC60FFBE541BFCCEFE26FC3F" box="[326,416,877,903]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="14" pageNumber="154">Mexico</collectingRegion>
is larger and it has a more regular and stronger axial sculpture.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
